# Maven Architecture & Internal Working

## Maven Architecture

```text
                👨‍💻 Developer
                     │
                     ▼
                  pom.xml
                     │
                     ▼
                Maven Engine
                     │
        ┌────────────┴────────────┐
        ▼                         ▼
 Local Repository          Central Repository
(.m2 folder in PC)        (Internet Server)
        │                         │
        └────────────┬────────────┘
                     ▼
                 Java Project
```

---

# Step 1 — Developer

Developer sirf project ki information aur required dependencies `pom.xml` me likhta hai.

Example:

```xml
<dependency>
    <groupId>org.projectlombok</groupId>
    <artifactId>lombok</artifactId>
    <version>1.18.38</version>
</dependency>
```

Developer ko manually JAR download karne ki zarurat nahi hoti.

---

# Step 2 — pom.xml

`pom.xml` ka full form hai:

**Project Object Model**

Ye Maven project ki blueprint file hoti hai.

Isme project ki important information hoti hai:

* Project Name
* Version
* Java Version
* Dependencies
* Plugins
* Build Configuration

Maven isi file ko padhkar project ko build karta hai.

---

# Step 3 — Maven Engine

Jab project build ya reload hota hai, Maven sabse pehle `pom.xml` ko read karta hai.

Phir check karta hai:

> "Kya required dependency Local Repository (`.m2`) me already available hai?"

Agar **Yes**, to wahi dependency use kar leta hai.

Agar **No**, to Maven Central Repository par request bhejta hai.

---

# Step 4 — Local Repository (.m2)

Default Windows Location:

```text
C:\Users\<Username>\.m2\repository
```

Ye Maven ka local storage hai.

Example:

```text
.m2
└── repository
    ├── mysql
    ├── springframework
    ├── lombok
    ├── junit
    └── jackson
```

Ek baar dependency download ho jaye to future me isi folder se use hoti hai.

---

# Step 5 — Central Repository

Agar dependency Local Repository me nahi milti, to Maven internet par available **Maven Central Repository** se us dependency ko download karta hai.

Flow:

```text
Developer
    ↓
pom.xml
    ↓
Maven Engine
    ↓
Local Repository (.m2)
    ↓
Not Found
    ↓
Maven Central Repository
    ↓
Download
    ↓
Save in .m2
    ↓
Project Ready
```

---

# Real Life Analogy

Socho tumhare ghar me ek Store Room hai.

* **Store Room** = Local Repository (.m2)
* **Market** = Maven Central Repository

Agar samaan ghar me mil gaya, to market nahi jaoge.

Agar ghar me nahi mila, tab market jaakar lekar aaoge.

Maven bhi exactly isi tarah kaam karta hai.

---

# Repository Types

## 1. Local Repository

* User ke computer me hota hai.
* Downloaded dependencies yahin store hoti hain.

## 2. Central Repository

* Maven ki official online repository.
* Internet se dependencies download hoti hain.

## 3. Remote Repository

* Company ya organization ki private repository.
* Enterprise projects me use hoti hai.

